@Francis

Isn't it interesting how our cultures differ? Some of your quintessential American experiences are utterly alien to me, and vice versa. Take bingo - it evokes fond memories for you, and if I know anything about it at all then only from some tropey appearances in fiction. Ditto Elks clubs - I first heard of them in these puzzles and I still am largely cluess as to what they are about. I'm looking at some info online as I'm writing this: apparently it's "a nationwide brotherhood dedicated to community service, patriotism, and mutual aid." The very concept is alien to me - we've never had anything like that over here in my lifetime.

Many of my fond childhood memories involve Park Kultury w Powisinie - the Powsin (that's a place name) Park of Culture. It is an extensive recreational area run by the city, with sport facilities, picnic areas, bars, a swimming pool, an outdoor theater, outdoor gyms, playgrounds, chess tables, all pleasantly shaded by the trees of the Kabacki Forest. Every major Polish city, and many towns, too, have such a place, and they are generally a thing all over Eastern Europe. You might think: "Hey! We have recreational areas, too!", and sure, you do, but they don't *feel* the same as ours. Us Eastern Europeans have a culture of spending time at these places, and we do it differently than you do, albeit the differences are hard to describe. You have an intrinsic understanding of what an Elk's lodge is, as do I regarding Park Kultury.

@Andrzej

I think I kind of get a sense of what you are talking about in your recreational areas.  I've spent very little time in Europe, and virtually non east of the former East Germany.  But I maybe feel it from nineteenth and early twentieth century paintings of Europe I've seen here and there.

But I do think it's quite cool that though our lives are quite different, the memories and fondness for them resonate inside us in nearly identical ways.

